{"version":3,"timestamp":"2026-02-11T05:40:51.355Z","sessions":{"e785666ebe38af9f":{"agent":"claude","model":"claude-opus-4-6","prompts":[{"id":94,"timestamp":"2026-02-11T04:12:26.503Z","content":"Base directory for this skill: /Users/marko/.claude/plugins/cache/superpowers-marketplace/superpowers/4.1.1/skills/writing-plans\n\n# Writing Plans\n\n## Overview\n\nWrite comprehensive implementation plans assuming the engineer has zero context for our codebase and questionable taste. Document everything they need to know: which files to touch for each task, code, testing, docs they might need to check, how to test it. Give them the whole plan as bite-sized tasks. DRY. YAGNI. TDD. Frequent commits.\n\nAssume they are a skilled developer, but know almost nothing about our toolset or problem domain. Assume they don't know good test design very well.\n\n**Announce at start:** \"I'm using the writing-plans skill to create the implementation plan.\"\n\n**Context:** This should be run in a dedicated worktree (created by brainstorming skill).\n\n**Save plans to:** `docs/plans/YYYY-MM-DD-<feature-name>.md`\n\n## Bite-Sized Task Granularity\n\n**Each step is one action (2-5 minutes):**\n- \"Write the failing test\" - step\n- \"Run it to make sure it fails\" - step\n- \"Implement the minimal code to make the test pass\" - step\n- \"Run the tests and make sure they pass\" - step\n- \"Commit\" - step\n\n## Plan Document Header\n\n**Every plan MUST start with this header:**\n\n```markdown\n# [Feature Name] Implementation Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task.\n\n**Goal:** [One sentence describing what this builds]\n\n**Architecture:** [2-3 sentences about approach]\n\n**Tech Stack:** [Key technologies/libraries]\n\n---\n```\n\n## Task Structure\n\n```markdown\n### Task N: [Component Name]\n\n**Files:**\n- Create: `exact/path/to/file.py`\n- Modify: `exact/path/to/existing.py:123-145`\n- Test: `tests/exact/path/to/test.py`\n\n**Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\n```python\ndef test_specific_behavior():\n    result = function(input)\n    assert result == expected\n```\n\n**Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `pytest tests/path/test.py::test_name -v`\nExpected: FAIL with \"function not defined\"\n\n**Step 3: Write minimal implementation**\n\n```python\ndef function(input):\n    return expected\n```\n\n**Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `pytest tests/path/test.py::test_name -v`\nExpected: PASS\n\n**Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add tests/path/test.py src/path/file.py\ngit commit -m \"feat: add specific feature\"\n```\n```\n\n## Remember\n- Exact file paths always\n- Complete code in plan (not \"add validation\")\n- Exact commands with expected output\n- Reference relevant skills with @ syntax\n- DRY, YAGNI, TDD, frequent commits\n\n## Execution Handoff\n\nAfter saving the plan, offer execution choice:\n\n**\"Plan complete and saved to `docs/plans/<filename>.md`. Two execution options:**\n\n**1. Subagent-Driven (this session)** - I dispatch fresh subagent per task, review between tasks, fast iteration\n\n**2. Parallel Session (separate)** - Open new session with executing-plans, batch execution with checkpoints\n\n**Which approach?\"**\n\n**If Subagent-Driven chosen:**\n- **REQUIRED SUB-SKILL:** Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development\n- Stay in this session\n- Fresh subagent per task + code review\n\n**If Parallel Session chosen:**\n- Guide them to open new session in worktree\n- **REQUIRED SUB-SKILL:** New session uses superpowers:executing-plans\n","tools":{"read":48},"duration":344},{"id":95,"timestamp":"2026-02-11T04:18:10.659Z","content":"<task-notification>\n<task-id>a931048</task-id>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Review cross-cutting concerns\" completed</summary>\n<result>Now I have a thorough understanding of all the changes. Let me compile my review.\n\n---\n\n## Cross-cutting PR #31 Review\n\n### What was done well\n\nThe overall structure of this PR is sound. The migration from `ICache` (synchronous, `HashMap`-based) to `AsyncICache` (`scc::HashMap`-based with InFlight/Available state machine) is a significant undertaking that has been executed thoughtfully. The introduction of `CompositeFs` to deduplicate delegation logic across `MesaFS` and `OrgFs` is a good architectural improvement. The feature-gated OTLP integration is cleanly separated with proper `#[cfg]` annotations.\n\nThe test coverage for `AsyncICache` is commendable -- 41 tests pass including concurrency scenarios like coalescing, InFlight waiting, and concurrent eviction.\n\n### Issue Report\n\n**Issue 1: `Ordering::Relaxed` on `InodeFactory::allocate` and `FileTable::allocate` is insufficient for correctness guarantees**\n\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/fs/icache/inode_factory.rs`, line 17\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/fs/icache/file_table.rs`, line 20\n- **Severity**: Low\n\n`Ordering::Relaxed` is technically correct for `fetch_add` on x86/ARM64 for monotonic counters because `fetch_add` is itself atomic -- you will never get duplicate values. The returned value is always unique across threads regardless of ordering. `Relaxed` is sufficient here because the only invariant is uniqueness, not happens-before relationships with other memory locations. The generated inode/fh is immediately used by the caller that received it.\n\nThat said, `Relaxed` means there are no ordering guarantees with respect to other memory operations. If a thread allocates an inode and then writes the ICB, another thread could (on weakly-ordered architectures) observe the ICB write before the counter increment. In practice, this does not matter here because the `scc::HashMap` insert that follows provides its own synchronization barriers. This is acceptable as-is.\n\n**Issue 2: `ensure_child_ino` and `evict_zero_rc_children` perform O(n) full table scans**\n\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/fs/mescloud/icache.rs`, lines 197-242\n- **Severity**: Medium\n\nBoth `evict_zero_rc_children` (line 199) and `ensure_child_ino` (line 217) use `self.inner.for_each(...)` which performs a synchronous linear scan over the entire inode table. For repositories with many files, this will become a bottleneck:\n\n- `ensure_child_ino` is called once per child during `RepoFs::lookup` and once per entry during `RepoFs::readdir`.\n- `evict_zero_rc_children` is called on every `readdir` call.\n- `for_each` iterates synchronously over the `scc::HashMap`, holding shard locks during iteration.\n\nFor a repo with 10,000 files, a `readdir` on a directory with 100 entries triggers 100 `ensure_child_ino` calls, each scanning all 10,000+ entries. This is O(n*m) where n = total inodes and m = directory entries.\n\nA parent-to-children index (e.g., `HashMap<Inode, HashSet<Inode>>`) would reduce these to O(1) lookups. This is not a correctness bug but will significantly impact performance at scale.\n\n**Issue 3: TOCTOU race in `ensure_child_ino`**\n\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/fs/mescloud/icache.rs`, lines 214-242\n- **Severity**: Low\n\n`ensure_child_ino` first scans for existing children via `for_each` (synchronous, non-atomic), then if not found, allocates a new inode and calls `insert_icb` (async). Between the scan returning \"not found\" and the insert completing, another concurrent call could also determine \"not found\" and allocate a duplicate inode for the same (parent, name) pair. Since the current FUSE adapter uses `&mut self` (single-threaded access), this is not a live bug today, but it will become one if/when the filesystem is made fully concurrent.\n\n**Issue 4: `evict_zero_rc_children` calls `forget(ino, 0)` which always evicts**\n\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/fs/mescloud/icache.rs`, line 206\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/fs/icache/async_cache.rs`, line 409\n- **Severity**: Low\n\nThe `forget` method at `async_cache.rs:409` uses `icb.rc() <= nlookups` to decide eviction. When `nlookups=0`, this becomes `icb.rc() <= 0`, which only evicts entries with `rc == 0`. The preceding `for_each` already filters for `rc == 0`, so this is correct. However, if the rc was incremented between the `for_each` scan and the `forget` call (by a concurrent `lookup`), the entry would survive eviction correctly because `rc > 0` would no longer satisfy the condition. This is safe behavior.\n\n**Issue 5: `delegated_forget` propagates nlookups to inner filesystem even when outer rc does not drop to zero**\n\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/fs/mescloud/composite.rs`, lines 211-226\n- **Severity**: High\n\n```rust\npub async fn delegated_forget(&mut self, ino: Inode, nlookups: u64) -> bool {\n    if let Some(idx) = self.slot_for_inode(ino)\n        && let Some(&inner_ino) = self.slots[idx].bridge.inode_map_get_by_left(ino)\n    {\n        self.slots[idx].inner.forget(inner_ino, nlookups).await;  // <-- always propagated\n    }\n    if self.icache.forget(ino, nlookups).await.is_some() {\n        // ... cleanup ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe `forget` is propagated to the inner filesystem unconditionally, regardless of whether the outer cache actually evicts the entry. Consider: the outer `MesaFS` has an inode with `rc=5`. The kernel forgets 2 lookups. `delegated_forget` calls `inner.forget(inner_ino, 2)`, which decrements the inner OrgFs's rc. But the outer rc only drops from 5 to 3 -- the outer entry survives. Meanwhile, the inner's rc might drop to zero and get evicted. Now the outer still has a live mapping to an inner inode that no longer exists. Subsequent operations (open, read) on that outer inode would try to forward to a dead inner inode.\n\nHowever, looking more closely at the previous implementation, it had the same pattern -- it unconditionally forwarded the forget to the inner fs. So this is not a regression, but it is a pre-existing design concern that was carried forward. The old code:\n```rust\nif let Some(idx) = self.org_slot_for_inode(ino)\n    && let Some(&org_ino) = self.org_slots[idx].bridge.inode_map_get_by_left(ino)\n{\n    self.org_slots[idx].org.forget(org_ino, nlookups).await;\n}\n```\n\nThis unconditional propagation works because the kernel's VFS layer manages the ref counts consistently -- a kernel forget with nlookups=N corresponds exactly to the N lookups it received. The inner and outer ref counts should move in lockstep because each outer lookup triggers exactly one inner lookup. So the inner and outer rc values should always match. This is correct by protocol invariant but fragile if any path ever increments outer rc without also incrementing inner rc.\n\n**Issue 6: `CompositeFs::delegated_readdir` returns a `readdir_buf` reference that aliases `&mut self`**\n\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/fs/mescloud/composite.rs`, lines 266-293\n- **Severity**: Low\n\nThe function takes `&mut self`, writes to `self.readdir_buf`, and returns `&self.readdir_buf`. This is safe because the borrow checker enforces that the returned reference's lifetime is tied to the `&mut self` borrow, preventing further mutation. The `Fs` trait's `readdir` method returns `&[DirEntry]` with lifetime tied to `&self`, and the `#[async_trait]` desugaring handles this correctly. No issue here.\n\n**Issue 7: `local` module is commented out without removal**\n\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/fs/mod.rs`, line 3\n- **Severity**: Low\n\n```rust\n// TODO: re-enable after icache refactoring is complete\n// pub mod local;\n```\n\nThe `local` module is commented out rather than removed. `Grep` confirms it is not referenced anywhere. The TODO comment is fine for tracking, but the source files for `local` presumably still exist on disk. If the refactoring is expected to take a while, consider whether the stale source files will diverge from the evolving icache API.\n\n**Issue 8: `RepoFs::lookup` calls `cache_attr` immediately after `get_or_resolve` which just set it**\n\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/fs/mescloud/repo.rs` (in the diff, around line 4539-4545)\n- **Severity**: Low\n\nIn `RepoFs::lookup`:\n```rust\nlet ino = self.icache.ensure_child_ino(parent, name).await;\nlet attr = self\n    .icache\n    .get_or_resolve(ino, |icb| icb.attr)\n    .await?\n    .ok_or(LookupError::InodeNotFound)?;\nself.icache.cache_attr(ino, attr).await;  // redundant\n```\n\n`get_or_resolve` already stores the resolved ICB (with `attr` set by the `RepoResolver`) back into the cache via `upsert_async`. The subsequent `cache_attr` call reads the ICB back out and sets `icb.attr = Some(attr)` -- but the attr is already set. This is a redundant async operation (two shard lock acquisitions for no reason). Not a bug, but unnecessary work.\n\n**Issue 9: OTLP exporter only initializes in \"Ugly\" mode, not in \"Pretty\" mode**\n\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/src/trc.rs`, lines 141-206\n- **Severity**: Medium\n\nThe OTLP exporter is only configured inside the `TrcMode::Ugly` branch. When the user has not set a log filter environment variable, the default mode is `TrcMode::丑` (pretty/compact), and no OTLP layer is added. This means developers running with default configuration will never export traces even if they have `__otlp_export` compiled in and an OTLP collector running.\n\nThis appears intentional based on the code comment at line 107-108: \"If the user provided an env_filter, they probably know what they're doing\" -> Ugly mode. But it is worth confirming this is the desired behavior. If a user wants both pretty output and OTLP export, that combination is currently impossible.\n\n**Issue 10: `opentelemetry-otlp` feature `reqwest-blocking-client` may cause issues in async context**\n\n- **File**: `/Users/marko/Desktop/gitfs/git-fs/Cargo.toml`, line 47\n- **Severity**: Medium\n\nThe dependency specifies:\n```toml\nopentelemetry-otlp = { version = \"0.29\", features = [\"http-proto\", \"trace\", \"reqwest-blocking-client\"], optional = true }\n```\n\nThe `reqwest-blocking-client` feature uses reqwest's blocking HTTP client, which internally spawns a thread and blocks. When used inside a tokio runtime (which this project uses), calling blocking reqwest from within an async context can panic or deadlock if the tokio runtime's thread pool is exhausted. The batch exporter's background thread should avoid this since it runs outside the async runtime, but this is a subtle footgun. Consider using `reqwest-client` (the async variant) instead, which works natively with tokio.\n\n### Summary\n\nThe PR is well-structured overall. The most significant findings are:\n\n| # | Severity | File | Description |\n|---|----------|------|-------------|\n| 5 | High | `composite.rs:211-226` | `delegated_forget` unconditionally propagates to inner FS (pre-existing design, not a regression) |\n| 2 | Medium | `icache.rs:197-242` | O(n) full table scans in `ensure_child_ino` and `evict_zero_rc_children` will not scale |\n| 9 | Medium | `trc.rs:141-206` | OTLP layer only active in Ugly mode; confirm this is intentional |\n| 10 | Medium | `Cargo.toml:47` | `reqwest-blocking-client` feature could cause issues in async context |\n| 1 | Low | `inode_factory.rs:17`, `file_table.rs:20` | `Ordering::Relaxed` is acceptable but worth documenting the reasoning |\n| 3 | Low | `icache.rs:214-242` | TOCTOU race in `ensure_child_ino` (not exploitable today due to `&mut self`) |\n| 7 | Low | `mod.rs:3` | Commented-out `local` module left behind |\n| 8 | Low | `repo.rs` (lookup) | Redundant `cache_attr` call after `get_or_resolve` |\n\nNo critical compilation or integration bugs were found. The feature flag gating is correctly implemented -- both `cargo check` and `cargo check --features __otlp_export` succeed cleanly, and clippy with all features reports no warnings. All 41 tests pass.</result>\n<usage>total_tokens: 132866\ntool_uses: 44\nduration_ms: 182657</usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-marko-Desktop-gitfs-git-fs/tasks/a931048.output","tools":{"write":1},"duration":88},{"id":96,"timestamp":"2026-02-11T04:19:38.768Z","content":"Base directory for this skill: /Users/marko/.claude/plugins/cache/superpowers-marketplace/superpowers/4.1.1/skills/subagent-driven-development\n\n# Subagent-Driven Development\n\nExecute plan by dispatching fresh subagent per task, with two-stage review after each: spec compliance review first, then code quality review.\n\n**Core principle:** Fresh subagent per task + two-stage review (spec then quality) = high quality, fast iteration\n\n## When to Use\n\n```dot\ndigraph when_to_use {\n    \"Have implementation plan?\" [shape=diamond];\n    \"Tasks mostly independent?\" [shape=diamond];\n    \"Stay in this session?\" [shape=diamond];\n    \"subagent-driven-development\" [shape=box];\n    \"executing-plans\" [shape=box];\n    \"Manual execution or brainstorm first\" [shape=box];\n\n    \"Have implementation plan?\" -> \"Tasks mostly independent?\" [label=\"yes\"];\n    \"Have implementation plan?\" -> \"Manual execution or brainstorm first\" [label=\"no\"];\n    \"Tasks mostly independent?\" -> \"Stay in this session?\" [label=\"yes\"];\n    \"Tasks mostly independent?\" -> \"Manual execution or brainstorm first\" [label=\"no - tightly coupled\"];\n    \"Stay in this session?\" -> \"subagent-driven-development\" [label=\"yes\"];\n    \"Stay in this session?\" -> \"executing-plans\" [label=\"no - parallel session\"];\n}\n```\n\n**vs. Executing Plans (parallel session):**\n- Same session (no context switch)\n- Fresh subagent per task (no context pollution)\n- Two-stage review after each task: spec compliance first, then code quality\n- Faster iteration (no human-in-loop between tasks)\n\n## The Process\n\n```dot\ndigraph process {\n    rankdir=TB;\n\n    subgraph cluster_per_task {\n        label=\"Per Task\";\n        \"Dispatch implementer subagent (./implementer-prompt.md)\" [shape=box];\n        \"Implementer subagent asks questions?\" [shape=diamond];\n        \"Answer questions, provide context\" [shape=box];\n        \"Implementer subagent implements, tests, commits, self-reviews\" [shape=box];\n        \"Dispatch spec reviewer subagent (./spec-reviewer-prompt.md)\" [shape=box];\n        \"Spec reviewer subagent confirms code matches spec?\" [shape=diamond];\n        \"Implementer subagent fixes spec gaps\" [shape=box];\n        \"Dispatch code quality reviewer subagent (./code-quality-reviewer-prompt.md)\" [shape=box];\n        \"Code quality reviewer subagent approves?\" [shape=diamond];\n        \"Implementer subagent fixes quality issues\" [shape=box];\n        \"Mark task complete in TodoWrite\" [shape=box];\n    }\n\n    \"Read plan, extract all tasks with full text, note context, create TodoWrite\" [shape=box];\n    \"More tasks remain?\" [shape=diamond];\n    \"Dispatch final code reviewer subagent for entire implementation\" [shape=box];\n    \"Use superpowers:finishing-a-development-branch\" [shape=box style=filled fillcolor=lightgreen];\n\n    \"Read plan, extract all tasks with full text, note context, create TodoWrite\" -> \"Dispatch implementer subagent (./implementer-prompt.md)\";\n    \"Dispatch implementer subagent (./implementer-prompt.md)\" -> \"Implementer subagent asks questions?\";\n    \"Implementer subagent asks questions?\" -> \"Answer questions, provide context\" [label=\"yes\"];\n    \"Answer questions, provide context\" -> \"Dispatch implementer subagent (./implementer-prompt.md)\";\n    \"Implementer subagent asks questions?\" -> \"Implementer subagent implements, tests, commits, self-reviews\" [label=\"no\"];\n    \"Implementer subagent implements, tests, commits, self-reviews\" -> \"Dispatch spec reviewer subagent (./spec-reviewer-prompt.md)\";\n    \"Dispatch spec reviewer subagent (./spec-reviewer-prompt.md)\" -> \"Spec reviewer subagent confirms code matches spec?\";\n    \"Spec reviewer subagent confirms code matches spec?\" -> \"Implementer subagent fixes spec gaps\" [label=\"no\"];\n    \"Implementer subagent fixes spec gaps\" -> \"Dispatch spec reviewer subagent (./spec-reviewer-prompt.md)\" [label=\"re-review\"];\n    \"Spec reviewer subagent confirms code matches spec?\" -> \"Dispatch code quality reviewer subagent (./code-quality-reviewer-prompt.md)\" [label=\"yes\"];\n    \"Dispatch code quality reviewer subagent (./code-quality-reviewer-prompt.md)\" -> \"Code quality reviewer subagent approves?\";\n    \"Code quality reviewer subagent approves?\" -> \"Implementer subagent fixes quality issues\" [label=\"no\"];\n    \"Implementer subagent fixes quality issues\" -> \"Dispatch code quality reviewer subagent (./code-quality-reviewer-prompt.md)\" [label=\"re-review\"];\n    \"Code quality reviewer subagent approves?\" -> \"Mark task complete in TodoWrite\" [label=\"yes\"];\n    \"Mark task complete in TodoWrite\" -> \"More tasks remain?\";\n    \"More tasks remain?\" -> \"Dispatch implementer subagent (./implementer-prompt.md)\" [label=\"yes\"];\n    \"More tasks remain?\" -> \"Dispatch final code reviewer subagent for entire implementation\" [label=\"no\"];\n    \"Dispatch final code reviewer subagent for entire implementation\" -> \"Use superpowers:finishing-a-development-branch\";\n}\n```\n\n## Prompt Templates\n\n- `./implementer-prompt.md` - Dispatch implementer subagent\n- `./spec-reviewer-prompt.md` - Dispatch spec compliance reviewer subagent\n- `./code-quality-reviewer-prompt.md` - Dispatch code quality reviewer subagent\n\n## Example Workflow\n\n```\nYou: I'm using Subagent-Driven Development to execute this plan.\n\n[Read plan file once: docs/plans/feature-plan.md]\n[Extract all 5 tasks with full text and context]\n[Create TodoWrite with all tasks]\n\nTask 1: Hook installation script\n\n[Get Task 1 text and context (already extracted)]\n[Dispatch implementation subagent with full task text + context]\n\nImplementer: \"Before I begin - should the hook be installed at user or system level?\"\n\nYou: \"User level (~/.config/superpowers/hooks/)\"\n\nImplementer: \"Got it. Implementing now...\"\n[Later] Implementer:\n  - Implemented install-hook command\n  - Added tests, 5/5 passing\n  - Self-review: Found I missed --force flag, added it\n  - Committed\n\n[Dispatch spec compliance reviewer]\nSpec reviewer: ✅ Spec compliant - all requirements met, nothing extra\n\n[Get git SHAs, dispatch code quality reviewer]\nCode reviewer: Strengths: Good test coverage, clean. Issues: None. Approved.\n\n[Mark Task 1 complete]\n\nTask 2: Recovery modes\n\n[Get Task 2 text and context (already extracted)]\n[Dispatch implementation subagent with full task text + context]\n\nImplementer: [No questions, proceeds]\nImplementer:\n  - Added verify/repair modes\n  - 8/8 tests passing\n  - Self-review: All good\n  - Committed\n\n[Dispatch spec compliance reviewer]\nSpec reviewer: ❌ Issues:\n  - Missing: Progress reporting (spec says \"report every 100 items\")\n  - Extra: Added --json flag (not requested)\n\n[Implementer fixes issues]\nImplementer: Removed --json flag, added progress reporting\n\n[Spec reviewer reviews again]\nSpec reviewer: ✅ Spec compliant now\n\n[Dispatch code quality reviewer]\nCode reviewer: Strengths: Solid. Issues (Important): Magic number (100)\n\n[Implementer fixes]\nImplementer: Extracted PROGRESS_INTERVAL constant\n\n[Code reviewer reviews again]\nCode reviewer: ✅ Approved\n\n[Mark Task 2 complete]\n\n...\n\n[After all tasks]\n[Dispatch final code-reviewer]\nFinal reviewer: All requirements met, ready to merge\n\nDone!\n```\n\n## Advantages\n\n**vs. Manual execution:**\n- Subagents follow TDD naturally\n- Fresh context per task (no confusion)\n- Parallel-safe (subagents don't interfere)\n- Subagent can ask questions (before AND during work)\n\n**vs. Executing Plans:**\n- Same session (no handoff)\n- Continuous progress (no waiting)\n- Review checkpoints automatic\n\n**Efficiency gains:**\n- No file reading overhead (controller provides full text)\n- Controller curates exactly what context is needed\n- Subagent gets complete information upfront\n- Questions surfaced before work begins (not after)\n\n**Quality gates:**\n- Self-review catches issues before handoff\n- Two-stage review: spec compliance, then code quality\n- Review loops ensure fixes actually work\n- Spec compliance prevents over/under-building\n- Code quality ensures implementation is well-built\n\n**Cost:**\n- More subagent invocations (implementer + 2 reviewers per task)\n- Controller does more prep work (extracting all tasks upfront)\n- Review loops add iterations\n- But catches issues early (cheaper than debugging later)\n\n## Red Flags\n\n**Never:**\n- Skip reviews (spec compliance OR code quality)\n- Proceed with unfixed issues\n- Dispatch multiple implementation subagents in parallel (conflicts)\n- Make subagent read plan file (provide full text instead)\n- Skip scene-setting context (subagent needs to understand where task fits)\n- Ignore subagent questions (answer before letting them proceed)\n- Accept \"close enough\" on spec compliance (spec reviewer found issues = not done)\n- Skip review loops (reviewer found issues = implementer fixes = review again)\n- Let implementer self-review replace actual review (both are needed)\n- **Start code quality review before spec compliance is ✅** (wrong order)\n- Move to next task while either review has open issues\n\n**If subagent asks questions:**\n- Answer clearly and completely\n- Provide additional context if needed\n- Don't rush them into implementation\n\n**If reviewer finds issues:**\n- Implementer (same subagent) fixes them\n- Reviewer reviews again\n- Repeat until approved\n- Don't skip the re-review\n\n**If subagent fails task:**\n- Dispatch fix subagent with specific instructions\n- Don't try to fix manually (context pollution)\n\n## Integration\n\n**Required workflow skills:**\n- **superpowers:writing-plans** - Creates the plan this skill executes\n- **superpowers:requesting-code-review** - Code review template for reviewer subagents\n- **superpowers:finishing-a-development-branch** - Complete development after all tasks\n\n**Subagents should use:**\n- **superpowers:test-driven-development** - Subagents follow TDD for each task\n\n**Alternative workflow:**\n- **superpowers:executing-plans** - Use for parallel session instead of same-session execution\n","tools":{"read":54,"edit":37},"duration":4844}],"startedAt":"2026-02-11T04:12:26.502Z"}},"files":{"Cargo.toml":[{"session":"e785666ebe38af9f","lines":"47","prompt":96}]}}
